<span id="freeTextContainer4714914761298524499">[<b>3.5 stars</b>]<br/><br/><i>&quot;The ornament of beauty, Shakespeare wrote, is suspect.<br/>And he was right.<br/>But beauty itself, unadorned and unaffected, is sacred, I think, worthy of our awe and our loyalty.&quot;</i><br/><br/>Another solid addition to the Kenzie &amp; Gennaro series. These books are by no means mind-blowing crime/thrillers but they are exciting, engaging and just enjoyable enough to keep me reading them. Definitely aged a bit in terms of how Lehane writes about Gennaro through Kenzie&apos;s POV—I could do with less ogling of her </span>
  <span id="freeText4714914761298524499" style="display:none">[<b>3.5 stars</b>]<br /><br /><i>"The ornament of beauty, Shakespeare wrote, is suspect.<br />And he was right.<br />But beauty itself, unadorned and unaffected, is sacred, I think, worthy of our awe and our loyalty."</i><br /><br />Another solid addition to the Kenzie &amp; Gennaro series. These books are by no means mind-blowing crime/thrillers but they are exciting, engaging and just enjoyable enough to keep me reading them. Definitely aged a bit in terms of how Lehane writes about Gennaro through Kenzie's POV—I could do with less ogling of her body. But I do like what he has done with their relationship over the course of the first three books. </span>
