<div id="review_25422552" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/25422552" />
    <a title="Rob" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/217393-rob"><img alt="Rob" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/25422552?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rob" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rob" href="/user/show/217393-rob">Rob</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780727856760" href="/book/show/21684.Sacred">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer25422552" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15536858144671868618"><b>
  <u>The part in bold applies to the entire Patrick Kensie / Angie Gennero series.</u>
</b><br/><br/><b>After watching the moving &apos;Gone Baby Gone&apos; I wanted to read this series of books. I wasn&apos;t disappointed. The stories may not be classics, but they grab you and you want to read to the end. Most importantly for me, I like the main characters. Even when they do things that make me mad, it feels like when I&apos;m mad at a friend and I know I&apos;ll get over it. I can relate to them and I feel like they&apos;re my friends even when </b></span>
  <span id="freeText15536858144671868618" style="display:none"><b>
  <u>The part in bold applies to the entire Patrick Kensie / Angie Gennero series.</u>
</b><br /><br /><b>After watching the moving 'Gone Baby Gone' I wanted to read this series of books. I wasn't disappointed. The stories may not be classics, but they grab you and you want to read to the end. Most importantly for me, I like the main characters. Even when they do things that make me mad, it feels like when I'm mad at a friend and I know I'll get over it. I can relate to them and I feel like they're my friends even when I want to slap them and tell them to get their shit together.<br />The stories are good, but not always pretty and these books are not for kids. A lot of themes appear in these books. Sex, Violence, Abuse, Love, Lust, Envy, and sometimes all of them mixed together. These aren't really the main theme of the books, but there are plenty of backstories and sub-plots in these books and anything goes.</b><br /><br /><u>Sacred</u> is the third book in the series. It was probably the hardest of all of them to figure out what was going on. The books follow the pretty common format of twist, twist, twist - find a clue/discover something - twist, shock - find a clue - etc. Then there's the wrap up at the end where everything is explained. I like this kind of story whethere it's in a book or a movie, or even a TV show, and I'm usually pretty good at figuring it out before the reveal. Part of the fun for me is trying to figure out the whole thing before the characters in the story do. If I'm right, I get to enjoy watching the characters catch up with me. It's sort of the same pleasure you get from reading a book or watching a movie a second time. The pleasure of watching the characters get where you know they are going is as much fun for me as watching them get to some unknown conclusion. Some people don't like knowing or having guessed the ending, but I do. <br /><br />I also like not having it all figured out and actually being surprised by some or all of the ending. There were parts of this book I just didn't see coming. That made it fun.<br /><br /><i>
  <b>
    <u>I don't think any of what I put in my review is a spoiler, but if anyone disagrees, please say so in the comments. I don't think saying a mystery is better at keeping its secrets or has a more surprising ending than other mysteries is a spoiler, but I suppose a spoiler is in the eye of the reader. If anyone sees that as a spoiler, then I guess it is, and I'll check the box in my review. Please don't be shy.</u>
  </b>
</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="15536858144671868618" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


