<div id="review_754641642" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/754641642" />
    <a title="David Goode" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14310264-david-goode"><img alt="David Goode" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1435711096p2/14310264.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/754641642?book_show_action=true">Nov 01, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Goode" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Goode" href="/user/show/14310264-david-goode">David Goode</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780062224040" href="/book/show/16248209-sacred">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14310264-david-goode?shelf=read-2013">read-2013</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14310264-david-goode?shelf=books-i-own">books-i-own</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer754641642" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15497370265767393996">I read this book in 3 days. While reading it was like &apos;duuude this book is goooooood, so much action, so many twists, give me more, give me more&apos;. But now thinking about it in retrospect, having completed the whole thing it has more or less left me pretty dissatisfied. I read it a couple of weeks ago and it already feels a little forgettable. The book definitely mellows out from the first two. It explores more the relationship between Patrick and Angie, which is a good thing, and also changes th</span>
  <span id="freeText15497370265767393996" style="display:none">I read this book in 3 days. While reading it was like 'duuude this book is goooooood, so much action, so many twists, give me more, give me more'. But now thinking about it in retrospect, having completed the whole thing it has more or less left me pretty dissatisfied. I read it a couple of weeks ago and it already feels a little forgettable. The book definitely mellows out from the first two. It explores more the relationship between Patrick and Angie, which is a good thing, and also changes the scenery and takes a turn from the streets of Boston down to Florida, which is also a good thing. Overall though I felt like it was a bit of a genre filler, more generics, less Lehane. I suspect after the success of the first two novels his publisher wanted him to churn another book out as quick as possible and this is what came out. <br /><br />The general story arch is basically a multi-billionaire hiring the duo to find his daughter who has run away. Oh, and that also he is dying of cancer and only has a limited time to live. It's a pretty intriguing story and so for the once over read, if you have read the first two, then I would recommend it, simply because I think the whole series is worth the investment. I wouldn't read it stand alone though. There were a couple of plot turns where I was just like "really?" but that was the exception not the rule. That's the great thing about Lehane, I feel he is pretty founded in his realism.<br /><br />So stack this read up against the first two books in the series and, to me, it doesn't stack up as strong. It is/was still an enjoyable read and it was nice to see things progress across the series. Looking forward to Gone baby Gone next!<br /><br /><b>Rating: 5/10</b><br /><br />1/10 - Perfect for starting a cozy fire at home.<br />2/10 - Drudgery. Not even worth borrowing from a friend.<br />3/10 - Forgettable.<br />4/10 - Maybe some pockets of goodness, but still forgettable.<br />5/10 - A mostly satisfying read. While some things left me feeling ‘bleargh’, there was more to like than dislike. <br />6/10 - An interesting and at times compelling read.<br />7/10 - Definitely worth the time, brilliant writing, recommended heartily.<br />8/10 - DAAAAAMNNNN. Will most likely recommend it to your cat it's that good.<br />9/10 – How is this writing even possible? A book you put down even three pages and think, “Are you for real?”. A true masterpiece.<br />10/10 - … <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15497370265767393996" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


